Social Media Checklist 
Do’s
- Use strong privacy settings to control who sees your posts.
- Think before posting — consider how it may affect your reputation.
- Give credit when sharing someone else’s work or ideas.
- Engage respectfully in online discussions.
- Use social media to build professional networks and share academic achievements.
Don’ts
- Don’t share personal information like phone numbers or addresses publicly.
- Don’t post offensive or discriminatory content.
- Don’t rely on unverified sources for academic work.
- Don’t overshare daily details that compromise your privacy.
- Don’t engage in cyberbullying or spread rumors.

Project Report
One situation where poor digital communication caused a real problem was when a student posted negative comments about a professor on social media. The post quickly spread among peers, damaging the professor’s reputation and creating tension between the student and faculty. This incident highlighted how impulsive online communication can have lasting consequences. Instead of venting frustrations publicly, the student could have addressed concerns directly through email or a private meeting. Responsible digital communication requires professionalism, respect, and awareness of the impact of online actions. By choosing appropriate channels and maintaining a constructive tone, misunderstandings can be avoided, and relationships preserved. This example shows why digital literacy and etiquette are essential for students navigating academic and professional environments.

